\fs32 3. Governance and Security\par
\fs24 Decentralization at my_DEX is not limited solely to technology; it also extends to governance (project steering & decision-making) as well as a collaborative security concept. As it is a financial system, robust security mechanisms take priority\f3\emdash\f0 from technical safeguards against attacks to rules regarding which assets can be traded. Simultaneously, the project's development and evolution will occur democratically and transparently, preventing sole decision-making authority by founders or developers.\line\par
\b 3.1 Community Governance\par
\b0 From the outset, my_DEX is designed as a community-driven project. Crucial decisions are made collectively, for example through stakeholder voting or an on-chain governance module (potentially via a DAO model\f3\emdash\f0 a decentralized autonomous organization). No single actor, whether founder or development team, can unilaterally alter rules or steer the project without community consent. This ensures my_DEX remains true to its vision and evolves in the interest of its users. Possible governance elements could include:\par

\pard{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf4\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b DAO Token or Voting Rights\b0 : Potential issuance of governance tokens to users, developers, and node operators, enabling votes on protocol changes, addition of new features, or allocation of reserve funds. Importantly, this token is not intended for speculative purposes but purely for participation in governance.\par
{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}\b Transparency\b0 : All decisions, development steps, and financial flows (such as fee distribution in pools, see Section 4) are published transparently. Similar to an open-source project on GitHub, project steering is fully traceable, with logs and proposals publicly accessible.\par
{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}\b Role of the Founder\b0 : Despite initiating the project and his involvement, the founder of my_DEX occupies a subordinate role in governance. Although receiving a predefined compensation (see fee model), he holds no special privileges in operational decision-making. This prevents the project from aligning too closely with individual interests. The founder's primary responsibilities are communicating the long-term vision and coordinating the team, especially in the project's initial phase.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 This collaborative governance ensures that my_DEX does not depend on individual convictions but is a consensus-driven product of the community. Changes to the protocol\f3\emdash\f0 such as adding new trading pairs, modifying fee models, or updating security policies\f3\emdash\f0 can thus be collectively decided. This strengthens the legitimacy and acceptance of each rule and builds user trust.\par
\par
\b 3.2 Security and Network Hardening\par
\b0 Security is the highest priority for my_DEX\f3\emdash\f0 after all, it involves managing real assets. The security concept is multi-layered, addressing various potential threats from technical attacks to abusive platform use.\par
\par
\b Protection Against Malicious or Manipulated Nodes\b0 : Because the network is open, the possibility of Sybil attacks (many fake nodes controlled by a single attacker) and malicious participants must be accounted for. my_DEX counters this through strategic network hardening:\par

\pard{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf4\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b Identity Verification for Nodes\b0 : While anyone can generally start a node, certain advanced network privileges (e.g., voting rights in governance or special routing functionalities) may be tied to verifying a unique identity. This verification might occur through stake deposits, reputation systems, or Web-of-Trust mechanisms. Crucially, this process is decentralized and privacy-preserving\f3\emdash\f0 for example, through pseudonymous digital certificates issued by the community. An attacker would face prohibitively high effort and cost to introduce mass false identities.\par
{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}\b Redundancy and Distribution\b0 : The my_DEX network is designed such that the failure or compromise of individual nodes does not threaten overall functionality. Data such as order books or transaction histories are redundantly (and encrypted) distributed across multiple nodes, preventing any single node from becoming a critical "beacon." If a node feeds false information (e.g., forged orders), other nodes can detect and isolate it through comparative verification.\par
{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}\b Monitoring and Audits\b0 : Similar to how Bitcoin miners discard invalid blocks, my_DEX nodes reject invalid transactions or swaps. At regular intervals, the community can conduct security audits of the open-source code (Rust\f3\rquote\f0 s clarity supports this auditability). Additionally, Watchtowers (mentioned in Section 2.3) help prevent fraud in payment channels by immediately intervening if outdated channel states are published\f3\emdash\f0 in such cases, the fraudulent node loses its deposited funds. This principle secures Lightning channels and is integral to my_DEX's security model.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b Blacklist Mechanism (Protection Against "Dirty" Coins)\b0 : A unique feature of my_DEX is a planned \b blacklist/whitelist mechanism\b0  for assets. To protect users from coins of questionable origin (such as verifiably stolen coins from hacks or otherwise sanctioned funds), the community can add addresses or UTXOs to a blacklist. Trades involving these blacklisted coins would then be automatically rejected or flagged by the protocol. This mechanism safeguards users, preventing them from unknowingly trading "tainted" assets that could later be frozen or legally targeted. The community holds sole authority to decide which coins or addresses are listed, ensuring no arbitrary control by individual developers. However, a sensitive balance is necessary: as my_DEX commits to censorship resistance, the blacklist function will be used sparingly and transparently, exclusively to mitigate clear-cut fraud or illegal activities without impairing legitimate users' freedom to trade.\par
\b No Risky Products\b0 : In line with security and ethical guidelines, my_DEX has deliberately decided not to offer interest-bearing products, leverage, derivatives, or highly speculative financial instruments. The platform\f3\rquote\f0 s focus is solely on the direct trade of cryptocurrencies (spot trading). This decision has multiple reasons:\par

\pard{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf4\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1 Such features (margin trading, futures, etc.) significantly increase complexity, burdening both technical implementation and the security architecture.\par
{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}Leveraged products encourage speculative behavior and carry risks of substantial losses, contradicting the project's aim of responsibly serving a broad, potentially inexperienced user base.\par
{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}By avoiding derivatives, my_DEX reduces exposure to regulatory ambiguities. The platform explicitly positions itself as purely a facilitator of crypto-to-crypto trades, offering fewer legal vulnerabilities than derivative trading venues.\par
{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}Security-wise, this approach means my_DEX avoids complex computations for liquidations, interest calculations, or similar tasks, reducing potential points of failure.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 Although this restriction might appear limiting at first glance, it actually embodies the my_DEX vision: simplicity, transparency, and safety. Users can confidently rely on the platform being free of hidden risks. Those trading on my_DEX will always exchange one real coin for another\f3\emdash\f0 no more, no less.\par
