\fs32 4. Compensation Model (Fees & Incentives)\par
\fs24 A decentralized network can only function successfully if all participants are fairly compensated for their contributions. For this reason, my_DEX introduces a thoughtfully designed fee and compensation model that provides incentives for developers and node operators, while simultaneously remaining sustainable and equitable. The goal is to distribute the financial revenues generated from ongoing operations (trading fees) in a way that covers development, network maintenance, and future sustainability.\line\par
\b Trading Fees\b0 : A small fee is charged for each successfully executed transaction on my_DEX (for example, a percentage of the trade volume or a minimal fixed amount for very small trades). These fees are not collected by a central entity; instead, they are automatically distributed by the protocol. Distribution occurs into three pools:\par
\par
\b Pool 1 \f3\endash\f0  Founder & Developers (60% of fees)\b0 : This pool rewards those who initiated and continue developing the project. 60% of all fees flow into this pool, distributed as follows:\par

\pard{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf4\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1 10% of total fees are designated for the founder. This honors the initial vision, risk assumption, and ongoing coordination efforts contributed by the founder.\par
{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}90% of Pool 1 fees (equating to 54% of total fees) go to the developer team. With an envisioned team of approximately 30 active core developers, each developer would receive about 3% of the total fees. Naturally, this distribution can be adjusted should the team expand or contract, but the core idea is to fairly compensate all active contributors. By directly participating in the project's success, developers are continually incentivized to improve and popularize my_DEX. New contributors can also proportionally benefit from this model, promoting openness for open-source contributions.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b Pool 2 \f3\endash\f0  Full Node Operators (40% of fees)\b0 : This pool rewards network infrastructure\f3\emdash\f0 all full node operators providing computational power, bandwidth, and availability. Without them, there would be no decentralized network. 40% of all collected fees are proportionally distributed among these operators. A mechanism ensures distribution fairness and decentralization incentives:\par

\pard{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf4\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1 Each node reliably operational and actively forwarding transactions/orders receives a share of Pool 2.\par
{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}\b Cap\b0 : A maximum amount of $300 per node (in equivalent cryptocurrency) is distributed within a certain period (e.g., monthly). This cap ensures individual nodes do not disproportionately profit solely because they are situated in high-volume trading areas. After reaching this cap, further earnings are limited, incentivizing network expansion: new nodes can join to earn fees, rather than existing nodes exponentially accumulating profits.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b Pool 3 \f3\endash\f0  Reserve & Bonuses\b0 : If Pool 2 generates more fees than are distributed due to the node earnings cap (for instance, if trading activity significantly increases and fees exceed the $300-per-node limit), the surplus flows into Pool 3. This pool serves multiple purposes:\par

\pard{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf4\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b Liquidity Reserve\b0 : The network maintains a reserve fund to provide liquidity in exceptional situations\f3\emdash\f0 be it for emergency measures, securing particularly large atomic swaps, or temporarily addressing imbalances. This reserve can also function as an insurance fund, such as in the unlikely event of a technical error harming users.\par
{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}\b Performance-Based Bonus Payments\b0 : Nodes delivering exceptional performance can receive bonuses from Pool 3. For example, full nodes maintaining uptime over 95% or facilitating an unusually high number of transactions can receive additional compensation. This motivates operators to maintain node stability and performance, improving overall network quality.\par
{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}\b Future Investments\b0 : Excess funds could also be directed towards development through community decisions\f3\emdash\f0 for example, bounties for new features, security audits, or marketing campaigns for my_DEX. Since Pool 3 is managed collaboratively, democratic decisions will determine how best to utilize these resources for the ecosystem.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 This three-tiered compensation model ensures each stakeholder profile is appropriately addressed:\par

\pard{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf4\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1 Developers and the founder receive continuous compensation for their work and commitment\f3\emdash\f0 crucial for maintaining the long-term attractiveness of an open-source project (compared to potentially more lucrative jobs elsewhere).\par
{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}Node operators, forming the backbone of decentralization, have clear financial incentives to support the network, yet without enabling oligopolistic node dominance (due to caps and bonus mechanisms).\par
{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}The system incorporates reserves for growth and unforeseen events, contributing to long-term sustainability.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 Fees themselves are set at a moderate level to maintain attractiveness for traders. As Lightning already drastically reduces transaction costs, there is considerable leeway to set very low trading fees (significantly below 0.1% per trade, for instance), ensuring sufficient volume for filling the pools while remaining highly attractive to users.\par
